Please don't use exceptions for control flow in bmcweb.  This is documented in DEVELOPING.md, and prevents optimizations that decrease our binary size.
Done

Please use the more common looping mechanism until unpackProperties is better understood in a bmcweb context.  If this is a pattern you want to see happen, please update some of the existing code to use it, and we can evaluate it outside the context of new code.
Done
FYI, CI failure was likely a false positive.  We had a breaking change in boost URI, and this got caught in the crossfire.  I rebased it, and the rebase should give a better result.
Please link the merged PDI commit for this new API for cross reference.
Ack, I will put that information in commit message. In meantime you can view it here: https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/commit/4f9c09144b60edc015291d2c120fc5b33aa0bec2
Done

Didn't do a complete review, because there's things like "ReadingParametersFutureVersion" that make me think this is still a WIP, and makes me wonder if the phosphor-dbus-interfaces updates have been made to change this API.
Phosphor dbus-interfaces is already updated.
Aren't all of these parameters required?  Why are we using the optional pointer version here?

From schema point of view only name and id are required. Other parameters just happen to be supported by telemetry service backend. We can as well make them all mandatory I was just trying to implement it like other bmcweb endpoints implement GET requests.
Considering there's only one implementation of these, and they've been supported since the first version, it's pretty reasonable to make them required.  With that said, it's not a big deal.
Done
What is ReadingParametersFutureVersion?

The idea behind this name is to make it not breaking, currently telemetry backend supports ReadingParameters and ReadingParametersFutureVersion. When bmcweb starts using FutureVersion we change ReadingParameters to be exactly the same as ReadingParametersFutureVersion then we can do another commit to bmcweb to change the name to ReadingParameters and remove ReadingParametersFutureVersion from telemetry service backend.

Thanks to that we won't break anything. Other way around would be to sync changes in bmcweb and telemetry and click merge at the same time or monitor each package bump and ensure there are no new version of telemetry service before this is merged.

https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/commit/4f9c09144b60edc015291d2c120fc5b33aa0bec2

In prosphor dbus interfaces there is no ReadingParametersFutureVersion as this will be renamed shortly in backend then in bmcweb to ReadingParameters after this change is merged.

>  to change the name to ReadingParameters and remove ReadingParametersFutureVersion from telemetry service backend.

THen we have to do a breaking change anyway, it just delays it, and complicates testing and merges..  Just list the commit you you need that makes the breaking change, and we can just make sure they bump at the same time.  There's only one implementation of this, so it should be trivial to just bump them at the same time, which we'd have to do anyway later.
Done
calling .string() on a url is not required.  We have overloads to convert a boost url to json automatically.
Ack, I will fix it.
Done
nit, missing const.
Ack, I will fix it.
Done
I had to revert this back to non-const. readJson function needs non const reference as parameter.

Please don't brace construct basic values.  I can't think of any other place we do that, and it's less clear than just initializing to a known value.
Ack, I will fix it.

Why is error messages a property?  We shouldn't need to unpack this I think?

> After completing first request report will be in invalid state because it will be set to "Periodic", but schedule is not yet change

Are there more examples to this?  Seems like it's easily fixed by just making sure we set the schedule parameter first, before we set ReportType?

Another option would be a dedicated "update parameter" method, that allows patching all properties in a single request in an atomic way.

> This allows to implement "State" property correctly without creating copy of validation code in bmcweb and it is foundation to implement "Conditions" property in the future.

What are we trying to convey in the state property?  THat the report definition is in error?

Done.

"ErrorMessages" property was removed, PATCH method introduced in next change will use dedicated method that updates multiple properties at same time.

I'm not comfortable with bmcweb using this API.  it seems to be taking an array of type-safe things, and smashing them into a map.  This would normally be done with method arguments, which keeps the type/name pairs consistent.  Can you comment on why that wasn't done here?  As-written, this puts bmcweb in charge of the API interface (given that the actual api is a dict) which in our designs, it really shouldn't be in charge of.

All you said is true. Since we both agree on disadvantages I will try to explain why we did it in a different way and what advantages we think this solution has.


- Other services usually have methods with only few arguments, AddReport have quite a lot arguments and most of them are optional. This change in API simplifies creating scripts and tests scenarios for telemetry backend, because only few parameters can be provided instead of all of them.

- This also removes default values from bmcweb, all default values are kept in telemetry backend.

- It will be easier to add new features that require new parameters. Adding new parameter won't break anything. We can add new parameter in telemetry backend and it won't break the code that it is not using that new parameter yet. All script and tests that use dbus API will also keep working because changes in API won't break code anymore.

Dbus provides same signature as return value when we are performing GetAll. When Set is performed then sv is used. AddReport would have same signature of SetAll if it existed in dbus.

In my opinion this is more flexible and backward compatible than being forced to always pass all parameters in specified order.

> AddReport have quite a lot arguments and most of them are optional.

Does that significantly change things though?  There's other dbus methods with a large number of arguments.  Is there some limit on argument count?  We generally represent optional arguments using some kind of default;  Empty string for strings, 0, MIN_INT, or MAX_INT for numbers, epoch for time.  Is there a reason we couldnt' do that here?

> This also removes default values from bmcweb, all default values are kept in telemetry backend.

This is overall good, and agreed, that's a good design goal.  bmcweb should not be in charge of defaults (given that they're effectively business logic).

> It will be easier to add new features that require new parameters.

I'm not sure I agree with that.  It's only easier because we no longer have a typesafe API that can be inspected and reused.  That doesn't seem like an appropriate tradeoff to me.

> This would normally be done with method arguments, which keeps the type/name pairs consistent.

+1.

As a general rule, dbus enums in openbmc take the form of:

xyz.openbmc_project.Namespace.Enum.Value

This does not fit with redfish, and generally requires a conversion function to convert one enum to another, while handling errors.  As-written, either the service you tested against wasn't publishing the enum appropriately to the phosphor-dbus-interfaces standard, or this can't have passed the redfish service validator.
